time with patients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ethical frameworks would most strongly support implementing this policy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Virtue ethics","Deontological ethics","Care ethics","Narrative ethics","Utilitarianism"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUtilitarianism\u003C/strong\u003E would support this policy as it focuses on achieving the greatest good for the greatest number of people. The reduction in infection transmission would benefit many patients, staff and the broader community, outweighing the negative impact on individual families.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other ethical frameworks would approach this differently:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeontological ethics\u003C/strong\u003E would emphasize moral duties and principles, such as respecting patient autonomy and family rights, potentially opposing the restriction if it conflicts with these duties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVirtue ethics\u003C/strong\u003E would focus on what a virtuous healthcare provider would do, balancing compassion for patients and families with wisdom in ensuring public health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECare ethics\u003C/strong\u003E would emphasize the importance of maintaining relationships and emotional connections between patients and families, likely favouring more flexible visiting policies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENarrative ethics\u003C/strong\u003E would consider individual patient and family experiences, potentially advocating for a more context-sensitive approach rather than a rigid universal restriction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile all frameworks have value, utilitarianism\u0027s focus on maximising overall benefit makes it most aligned with implementing this policy for infection control purposes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Utilitarianism focuses on maximising benefits for the greatest number of people in ethical decision-making.","Deontological ethics emphasises moral duties and rules regardless of consequences.","Virtue ethics centres on the moral character and virtues of the healthcare provider rather than rules or outcomes."],"references":["Ahmer, A. Understanding the Ethical Theories in Medical Practice. Open Journal of Nursing. 2019. https://www.scirp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=90706","University of New South Wales. Ethics Cube [Internet]. Sydney: UNSW Medicine \u0026 Health; [cited 2025 Jan 30]. Available from: https://ethics.med.unsw.edu.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67782"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19168"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67782"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T12:13:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T12:14:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11902"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82616"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"